 - Candidate Document: Calculating BTU per natural gas flow is a crucial step in energy management, environmental impact assessments, and optimizing gas system efficiency. The BTU is a standard unit of heat content, used to measure the energy content of natural gas. To calculate BTU per natural gas flow, you need to know the flow rate and the heating value, typically given in BTUs per cubic foot. For example, if the heating value is 1000 BTU per cubic foot and the flow rate is 1000 cubic feet per hour, the calculation is:

\[ \text{BTU per hour} = \text{Flow rate} \times \text{Heating value} \]

This formula provides valuable insights into natural gas energy consumption, efficiency, and potential environmental impact, facilitating informed decisions for improvement. By understanding the BTU per natural gas flow, you can optimize your natural gas systems for maximum efficiency and minimize environmental impact.

By effectively incorporating these phrases, writers can add depth and precision to their writing, making it more engaging and understandable for readers.  - Candidate Document: Allow your pork tenderloin to rest at room temperature for 20-30 minutes, seasoned with salt, pepper, and your choice of herbs, ensuring even cooking and optimal flavor.

In a hot skillet, heat a small amount of oil over medium-high heat, then sear the pork tenderloin for 4-5 minutes on each side, creating a crispy browned crust.

Reduce the heat to medium and continue cooking for 10-15 minutes, or until the internal temperature reaches 145°F (63°C), ensuring a tender and juicy outcome.

Remove the pork from the skillet and let it rest for 5-10 minutes before slicing, allowing the juices to redistribute throughout the meat.

Slice the pork tenderloin against the grain and serve with your favorite sides, such as roasted vegetables or a side salad, for a mouth-watering and well-rounded meal.

Cut a healthy stem: Use clean, sharp scissors or pruning shears to cut a healthy stem or leaf off the plant, ensuring it has multiple nodes. This will increase the chances of successful rooting.

Prepare the cutting: Remove the lower leaves from the cutting to encourage root growth and prevent waterlogged soil.

Place the yucca cutting in a glass of water, changing it every 3-5 days to prevent mold growth and root rot.

Roots should develop within 1-2 weeks, at which point the cutting can be planted in a well-draining pot filled with a mix of potting soil and sand.
